title: For Sale:  375 Cheytac Package
postcontent:
Price negotiable.  Will consider accurate AR’s or more particularly an upper for partial trade.  Ok to ship if buyer covers it. This rifle is a 375 Cheytac, assembled over a year’s time and completed in Spring of 2015.  The heart of the rifle is a Stiller Tac-408 action which was made to order specifically for this build.  The barrel is a custom spec Brux 29” which is fluted with a twist rate of 1:11”.  In March of 2015, the barrel was fitted to the action and chambered by Mark King, of Mark King Rifles in Duncannon, PA.  Mark has a solid reputation for building world record setting bench rest rifles and does gunsmith work for the Pennsylvania State Police sniper rifles.  The Chamber was set up to allow the bullet to touch the lands of the rifling at max magazine length.  This was using Lehigh 330gr bore rider and Cutting Edge 352 gr solids.  Shoots the Sierra 350 gr match kings very well, too.  I have gotten 1/3 MOA with those. 
                The barreled action sits in a Cadex Dual Strike Chassis, acquired through GIG Long Range Systems in Port Orange, FL in January of 2015.  It has a 40moa top rail, folding stock with quick adjust cheek rest and length of pull.  Justin, of JMG Firearms in Montoursville, PA did the Cerakote work on the rifle, which is Federal Field Drab. 
                The bipod is a Long Range Accuracy Light Tactical Long Leg.  It cradles the forend tube establishing a solid center of gravity for stable shooting and quick recovery from recoil.  The feet are replaceable and come with the rubber caps on as well as a set of spike feet.  The Trigger is a Jewel set at 2lbs and can be adjusted heaver or lighter.  Up top sits a Nightforce ATACR 5-25x56 with the MOAR-T reticle.  With 120 MOA of travel, excellent glass and precise turrets, this made the rifle fairly easy to shoot at 2000 yards and has enough travel to dial to over 2600 yards, depending on the load.  The scope sits in an ERA-TAC one piece 20 moa mount.  This German made alloy mount is able to accept numerous accessories such as bubble levels, cosine indicators, rail sections and more.  The muzzle brake is a custom creation crafted by John Buhay of US Armament Corp.  It screws on via a 1x14 threads.  With the scope, bipod, and empty magazine, the rifle weighs 26 lbs.  It comes with two 7 round magazines and will accept an overall length of 4.460”. 
                As for accessories, it comes with a set up for reloading.  850 Federal large rifle magnum primers, ~9 lbs of Retumbo.  ~430 Sierra 350 gr bullets, all same lot.  I also have 40 Lehigh 330 gr and a few Cutting Edge 352 gr solids that would be excellent to try.  It comes with 45pcs of Cheytac provided brass with 3 loadings in each.  They have plenty of life left but I would suggest gathering up a fresh batch before seriously shooting it.  Cheytac dies are provided, as well as a Sinclair priming tool.  I have found 137 gr of Retumbo to be the biggest charge without the danger of excessive pressure signs.  With that charge, the Sierra bullets had a muzzle velocity of 3120 fps measured with a Magnetospeed.  The rifle, in its completed form is a year and a half old and has had ~150 rounds fired through it.

title: For Sale:  12 Gauge Police Magnum
postcontent: Remington 870 Police Magnum Shotgun.  Retired police weapon that rode around in cars but was not fired much.  Cosmetic condition is very good, mechanical condition is excellent.  Showing some handling marks.  Made to fire 3-inch magnum rounds.  20" barrel.  Magazine extensions can easily be added for 8-shot capacity.  I will only sell to the holder of a valid Tennessee Handgun Permit.  Flakes and lowball offers....please don't contact me.POLICE MODEL 870 DETAILS From the Remington website:  870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection. All Police shotguns are assembled in a special build area at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build Law Enforcement and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift. All parts that enter the special build area are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality. Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function. A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs. A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds. Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. Law Enforcement shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety. The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks.  The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty.  The Express model has a BEAD BLAST BLUE finish while the Police models utilize either High Luster bluing or Parkerization. The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing. The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a ball detent system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade synthetic magazine spring retainer lock down as used on the Express system. The receivers used in Police guns are vibra honed to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization or bluing.  Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.
